de.esoco.lib.expression.monad

Class Promise<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • de.esoco.lib.expression.monad.Promise<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Functor<T>, Monad<T,Promise<?>>

    public abstract class Promise<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements Monad<T,Promise<?>>
    A monad that promises to provide a value, typically asynchronously after some background computation.

      • ofAll

        public static <T> Promise<java.util.Collection<T>> ofAll(java.util.Collection<Promise<T>> rPromises)
        Converts a collection of promises into a promise of a collection of resolved values. The returned promise will only complete when all promises have completed successfully. If one or more promise in the collection fails the resulting promise will also fail.
        Parameters:

        Returns:
        A new promise containing a collection of resolved values or with FAILED state if an input promise failed

      • getState

        public abstract Promise.State getState()
        Returns the current state of this promise. Due to the asynchronous nature of promises a returned state of Promise.State.ACTIVE is only a momentary value that may not be valid anymore after this method returns. In general, it is recommended to prefer the monadic functions to operate on the completion of promises.
        Returns:
        The current state of this promise

      • onError

        public abstract Promise<T> onError(java.util.function.Consumer<java.lang.Throwable> fHandler)
        Returns a new promise that consumes the error of a failed promise. This method is non-blocking and will typically execute the given function asynchronously when the promise terminates because of an exception.

        In general, calls to the monadic functions map(Function), flatMap(Function), or then(Consumer) should be preferred to process values but a call to a consuming operation should typically appear at the end of a chain.

        Parameters:
        fHandler - The consumer of the the error that occurred
        Returns:
        The resulting promise

      • withTimeout

        public abstract Promise<T> withTimeout(long nTime,
                                       java.util.concurrent.TimeUnit eUnit)
        Defines the maximum time this promise may try to acquire the promised value before failing as unresolved. As promises are immutable objects this method will not modify the current instance but returns a new instance (if necessary) that will respect the given timeout.

        Although it depends on the actual underlying implementation, the timeout is typically only respected by blocking methods like Functor.orUse(Object).

        Parameters:
        nTime - The timeout value
        eUnit - The time unit
        Returns:
        The resulting promise

      • and

        public <V,R,N extends Monad<V,Promise<?>>> Promise<R> and(N rOther,
                                                          java.util.function.BiFunction<? super T,? super V,? extends R> fJoin)
        Combines this monad with another monad into a new monad of the same type. This is done by invoking Monad.flatMap(Function) on this instance and "lifting" the other monad by invoking it's Monad.map(Function) method. Therefore this type of method is sometimes also called "lift" or "liftM2".

        Implementations should override this method to return their own type but they can simply invoke the default implementation ( Monad.super.and(rOther, fJoin)) and cast the result to their own type. The explicit declaration in subclasses is necessary because of the limitations of Java's generic type system.

        Specified by:
        and in interface Monad<T,Promise<?>>
        Parameters:
        rOther - The other monad to combine with
        fJoin - A binary function that joins the values of both monads
        Returns:
        The new joined monad

      • isResolved

        public final boolean isResolved()
        Checks whether this promise has been successfully resolved. If it returns TRUE accessing the resolved value with the consuming methods like Functor.orUse(Object), Functor.orFail(), Functor.orThrow(Function), or Functor.orElse(Consumer) will not block and yield a valid result. This is just a shortcut for testing the state with getState() == RESOLVED.
        Returns:
        TRUE if this promise
